{"/service/ndnp/vi/batch_vi_cartier_ver01/data/sn94060041/00542866731/1924011901/0029.xml":{"full_text":"Are You\nReady?\nReading the signs, they plainly indicate that the busi\nness depression is permanently behind us.\nBusiness in general assumes a decidedly more opto\nmistic outlook, and the business man with vision is already\ncarefully laying his plans for the business revival that is\nupon us.\nOne of the first and most important actions should be\nyour association with the BANK that is in a position to\nbest serve your requirements from a financial and advis\nory standpoint.\nThis bank most cordially invites an interview with\nany one considering the establishment of new or additional\nbanking connections.\nAonfidence ^lever fletrayed\nI He uitizens National Dank\nof Pocomoke City, Md.\nBANK HABIT\nSAVING HABIT\nPROSPERITY\nOLD AGE COMFORTS\nElijah J. Schoolfield, President. Colmore E. Byrd, Cashier.\nJ. C. Stevenson, Trust Officer\nQuality\nis a much abused word, but NOT when applied to\nRoyster\u2019s\nFertilizers\nQUALITY is remembered long after PRICE is for\ngotten. If you have not already made arrangements for\nyour needs, we suggest you do so promptly.\nConsult bur nearest agent or write direct to\nF. S. Royster Guano Company\n1606-1613 Munsey Building\nBaltimore, Maryland\nOur Motto Is As Follows:\nQuality pr\u2018lce Service\n...O N...\nGeneral Merchandise\nSalt, Shingles, Lime, Coal, Terra-Cotta Pipe, Feeds, Etc.\nSpecial\nHaving been appointed exclusive agents\nin this territory for\nRoyal Breakfast Coffee\nWe are offering same for\n29 Cents a Pound\nGood as the best and for less money\nWHY PAY MORE?\nTRY IT!\nWEST WESSELS\nTasley, Virginia\nBRAND\nCoffee\nMERCHANTS WHOLESALE\nGROCERY COMPANY. Inc.\nPHILADELPHIA. PA\nPARKSLEY MARBLE WORKS\nE. H. HOWARD. Proprietor\nMOORE\nTelephone Xo. 3o F 3\n9 Manufacturers of\ni MARBLE AND GRANITE\nMONUMENTS\nCoping, Slabs, Markers and\nConcrete Building Blocks\nPARKSLEY, VA.\nSANFORD\n\nMrs. Carl Anderton is the guest of\nrelatives in Snow Hill.\nMrs. Elmer Anderton is the guest\nof her sister in Chester, Pa.\nMr. and Mrs. L. T. Fisher have\nbeen the recent guests of relatives in\nCrisfield.\nMr. and Mrs. Rufus Bailey, an\nj nounce the birth of a daughter on\ni December 21th, 1923.\nMrs. William Spencer Godwin is in\nthe Peninsula General Hospital to\nhave an operation performed.\ni We are glad to report that Miss\nViolet Godwin is convalescent from\na very serious appendicitis operation.\nI Those on the sick list are, Mrs. M.\nF. Drummond, Mrs. Almira Hall, Mrs.\nj G. F. Byrd and Eugenia, the little\ndaughter of Mr. and Mrs. Harry\nBundick and Mr. James Hall ,of G.\nj Messrs. W. W. and L. T. Fisher\nare the champion hog raisers of the\ncommunity. They butchered two on\nMonday so large that there were no\nscales in the town with capacity\nenough to weigh them. \u201cIf at first\nyou don\u2019t succeed try, try again.\u201d\nMr. Edward Ross and family have\nmoved to the old Kentucky farm; Mr.\nErnest Stant and family are living at\nthe Corbin farm, from whence Mr.\nRoss moved; Mr. Hance Byrd and\nfamily, of Salisbury, have purchased\nthe Stant place and are now living\nthere.\nThose home for the Christmas\nholidays were Mr. George Byrd, of j\nBuffalo, N. Y., and Mr. Neal Byrd, of\nV. M. I. Mr. and Mrs. Spencer Cor\nbin, of Pocomoke, with Mr. and Mrs.\nG. F. Byrd; Mr. and Mrs. James\nWitham, of Baltimore, Md.; Messrs.\nWinfred and Carlton Witham, of\nPhiladelphia, and Miss Pauline Hor\nsey, of Washington, with Mr. and\nMrs. M. E. Witham; Mr. and\nMrs. George Feddeman and daugh\nter, Althea, of Pocomoke, and\nMr. and Mrs. Stephen Corbin of\nNewport News, Mr. Paul Feddeman,\nof Philadelphia, and Mr. and Mrs. j\nPaul Walker, of Willis Wharf, with.\nMrs. Mary Feddeman, Miss Hilda j\nJustis, of Cape Charles, with Mr.j\nand Mrs. Arthur Justis, Mr. and j\nArthur Bender, of Cape Charles, with!\nMrs. Eslie Hall, Mr and Mrs. John\nMarshall and Mr. and Mrs. Ezekiel\nHolland, of Cape Charles, Mr. and!\nMrs. Jack Ryan, of Baltimore, and\nMr. and Mrs. Garner Miles, of Melfa,\nwith Mr. and Mrs. Noah Miles.\nHORNTOWN\nThe Misses Silverthorne entertain\ned at \u201cRook\u201d last Thursday evening.\nMiss Virginia Silverthorne spent\nSunday with her cousins, Misses Mar\nian and Mildred Hickman.\nMr. and Mrs. A. T. Hickman and\nfamily, of Silva, Va., spent Sunday\nwith her mother, Mrs. M. E. Wat\nson.\nMiss Hazel Sparrow, of New\nChurch, Va., spent the week-end with\nher grandmother Mrs. J. H. Marri\nner.\nMiss Grace Otwell of Temperance\nville, Va., spent the week-end with\nher parents Mr. and Mrs. W. T. Ot\nwell.\nMrs. Helen Ward, of Cape Charles,\nVa., has been a recent visitor at the\nhome of Mr. and Mrs. Lemuel Pen\nnewell.\nMiss Helen Slocomb, of New\nChurch, Va., spent the week-end\nwith her parents, Mr. and Mrs. T. H.\nSlocomb.\nMr. and Mrs. E. L. Wimbrow and\ntwo daughters, Eula and Ernestine,\nspent Sunday with Mr. and Mrs. J.\nR. Hickman.\nMr. Albert Wise, principal of our\nschool, spent the week-end with his\nparents, Mr. and Mrs. Ray Wise,, of\nOnancock, Va.\nMr. and Mrs. Jack Ward and\ndaughter, Patsie, of Salisbury, Md.,\nspent Sunday with her parents, Mr.\nand Mrs. W. D. Meelheim.\nThere will be prayer meeting atj\nthe Methodist Church Sunday even\ning at 7:30 p. m. Come out and en\njoy these meetings with us.\nThe Epworth League, of the M. E.\nChurch, meets every Friday evening\nat the Methodist Church. We have\nsome splendid programs. Everybody\ncome next Friday evening. We are\nsure you will enjoy it.\nSAXIS\nA number of our berry raisers are\ngetting their crates for this spring..\nCapt. and Mrs. Noah T. Miles left\nfor Baltimore, recently, to spend the\nwinter.\nMr. and Mrs. P. W. Taylor, of Bal\ntimore, have been visiting their\nbrother, Mr. J. L. Taylor.\nMr. \u201cBonny\u201d Moore, one of our\nmost prominent citizens and a leading\nmember of Saxis Baptist Church, died\nsuddenly Wednesday evening, Janu\nary 9th, while visiting his daughter,\nMrs. William Moore, of Crisiield, Md.\nHis remains were brought here and\nburial was in Saxis Baptist Cemetery\non Friday, January 11th. Surviving\nMr. Moore, are his wife and ten chil\ndren.\nMAPPSVILLE\nMessrs. Creston Gillespie and Sam\n.Wright are on the sick list.\nMiss Phyllis Savage returned home\nMonday from a week\u2019s visit with\nfriends at Delmar, Del.\nMr. and Mrs. William T. Hickman\nand two children, of Rue, spent the\nweek-end with her sister, Mrs. Claude\nBelote.\nQuite a number of our farmers\nattended the annual meeting of the\nProduce Exchange held at Onley, last\nFriday.\nMrs. George Feddeman and daugh\nter, Miss Althea, of Pocomoke, spent\nseveral days last week with her sister,\nMrs. H. K. Fisher.\nMr. Frank Taylor has returned to\nhis work in Franklin, Va., after hav\ning spent ten days with his family\nin the home of Mr. and Mrs. S. C.\nAbbott on the seaside.\nMaster William Davis has returned\nfrom Peninsula Hospital at Salisbury,\nwhere he went to have a finger\ntaken off, which was caused by him\nshooting a bullet from a small sized\npistol. He was threatened with lock\njaw. While he is still in a very weak\ncondition, we are glad to say he is\ndoing very nicely at this time.\nIN MEMORIAM\nIn sad but loving remembrance of\nmy dear husband, Southey Mapp, wh\u00ab\ndeparted this life one year ago, Jan\nuary 10th, 1923.\nDearest huoband, how I miss you,\nOnly God will ever know,\nI miss you more each day, dear hus\nband,\nThough long has been the year.\nI never can forget you, Southey,\nI miss you every place I go,\nYou have made a vacancy in our\nhome,\nThat never can be filled.\nDear is the grave where my husband\nlies,\nSweet is the memory that never dies,\nThe heart of my life is buried deep,\nUnder the sod where my husband\nSleeps.\nWhat a happy home I once enjoyed,\nHow sweet the memory still,\nBut death has left an aching void,\nThis world can never fill.\nI can never forget you, dear husband,\nNever shall your memory fade,\nSweetest thoughts shall ever linger,\nAround the grave where you are laid.\nWe will meet you some bright morn'\ning\nResting by the waters fair,\nYou\u2019ll be waiting our coming,\nIn the upper garden there.\nMy depths of sorrow I cannot tell,\nOf the loss of fhe one we loved so\nwell,\nYou are missed by all who knew you.\ndear father,\nAnd while you rest in peaceful sleep,\nYour sacred memory we will always\nkeep.\nBy his loving wife and children\nIN MEMORIAM\nIn sad but loving remembrance of\nmy dear husband and our dear father,\nJohn H. Marriner, who departed this\nlife one year ago, January 18, 1923.\nThe month of January once again\nis here,\nThe saddest to us of all the year,\nBecause it took from us away,\nOur dear husband and father, one\nyear ago today\nWhat a happy home we once enjoyed,\nHow sweet the memory still,\nBut death has left an aching void\nThe world can never fiill.\nPeaceful be thy rest dear husband,\nIt is sweet to breathe thy name,\nIn life we loved thee dearly,\nIn death we do the same.\nFriends may think we have forgotten\nthee,\nAnd our wounded hearts are healed,\nBut they little know the sorrow\nThat\u2019s within our hearts concealed.\nOur hearts are sad and lonely,\nOur grief too deep to tell,\nBut the time is coming soon,\nThat we may with thee dwell.\nBy his loving wife and children\nIN MEMORIAM\nIn memory of R. Duncan Kellam,\nwho fell asleep Christmas morning,\n1923, to await the glorious awakening\nof the redeemed.\nOh! how sad to part with loved ones,\nOh! how much of grief we bear;\nBut in the bright land of glory\nWe,shall be united there.\nHere the home ties often are broken,\nHere is left the vacant chair,\nBut in Heaven we shall meet thee,\nThere will be no parting there.\nOh! how sweet the thought to ponder,\nOh! the day, sweet, happy day,\nWhen we all shall meet up yonder,\nAnd shall ever with them stay.\nHis devoted mother,\nBettie Ward Kellam.\n666 quickly relieves Colds, Fe\nver and LaGrippe, Constipation,\nBiliousness and Headaches.\nMarvelous Record Made by Studebaker Big-Six\n475,000 Miles\nIn Everyday Service\nASSOCIATED TRANSIT CO., Inc.\nCONTRACT CARRIERS\nStudebaker Corporation of America,\n1250 So. Figueroa Street,\nLos Angeles, California.\nGentlemen:\nLos Angeles, Cal, Dec. 23, 1923\nStudebaker Big Six Touring Car, 1919 Model, Motor No. 7248, Serial No. 290,210 was\npurchased by this firm on Oct. 27th, 1920, and has been in our service for past three\nyears making two round trips daily hauling newspaper for the Los Angeles Times and\nLos Angeles Evening Express to Santa Barbara and intermediate points The daily\nmileage for six days in the week was in excess of four hundred miles, the seventh day\nit made only one round trip, of two hundred and twenty-five miles.\nAccording to our records, this car, tvhile in our possession traveled in excess of four\nhundred thousand (400,000) miles; averaged approximately fourteen miles to the gallon\not gasoline; and better than twenty thousand miles on a set of tires\n,,The1\u201c wasinactive service when turned over to you and has now been replaced\nwith a 1924 Studebaker Big Six. y\nYours very truly,\nAssociated Transit Co., Inc.\nBy- President\nSubscribed and sworn to before me this 23rd day of December, 1923.\nBenj. Wood,\nNotary Public in and for the County of Ventura, California.\nStudebaker Corporation,\n1250 S. Figueroa St.\nLos Angeles,. Calif.\nGentlemen:\nSimi, Calif., Dec. 22,1923\nStudebaker Big Six Touring Car, 1919 Model, Motor No. 7248, Series 290,210, was\npurchased by me on June 13, 1918, and was used by me up to Oct. 27,. 1920, during\nwhich time I drove the car a little over 94,000 miles, the same being used in' California,\nOregon, Washington, Wyoming, Nevada, Arizona and old Mexico, under all kinds of\nroads as well as climatic conditions.\nAccording to my records the car averaged 14 miles per gallon of gasoline, and\napproximately 1,000 miles per gallon of oil.\nYours very truly,\nSubscribed and sworn to before me this 22nd\nday of December, 1923.\nL. I. DinsmoreJ\nNotary Public in and for the County of Ventura, California.\nFenton Norman.\nThis veteran car has just reached New York City from Los Angeles. It bucked\nthe desert, conquered the snow and ice mountain passes, won its way through the quag\nmire of the middle Western roads and came all the way from coast to coast without\nroad delay except two punctuies. The car carries the orginal body, motor transmission\nand rear axle assemblies. No complete unit has ever been replaced. The mileage is\nequal to twenty trips around the world and it is a World\u2019s record for distance for any\nkind of automobile. Come in and we will give full particulars and show you the im\nprovements of the new models over the old.\nOnley\nOnley, Virginia\nLooking Ahead\nI AST Spring a total of 350,000 people were disappointed in\nnot being able to obtain deliveries of Ford Cars and Trucks,\nas orders were placed faster than cars could be produced.\nThe demand for Ford Cars and Trucks this Spring will, accord*\ning to all indications, be far greater than last Spring.\nWinter buying has been increasing at a greater rate than eve?\nbefore.\nActual retail deliveries the past 60 days\ntotaled 308,170 Ford Cars and Trucks, an\nincrease of 1,961 a day over a year ago.\nOver 200,000 people have already ordered Ford products on\nour purchase plan, the majority of whom will take delivery in\nthe Spring.\nThe above facts are given with the suggestion that you list your\norder promptly with a Ford dealer if you contemplate the pur\nchase of a Ford Car or Truck for use this Spring or Summer and\nwish to avoid delay in delivery. y\nYou Mod not pay cash lot your car. You can arrange to make a small deposit\ndeem, taking one of ike fcaUr.ce In easy payments. Or, you can buy on tbs\nFord Weekly Purchase Plan. This puts you on the preferred order\n1st and insures dJI'tsry of your ear at a lima to be determined by yourseH\nGet the Nearest Authorised Fori l-hxlm\nSubscribe for the Enterprise, $1.50 per yea","height":"26852","width":"20108"}}
